TORONTO (AP) — Los Angeles Dodgers manager Dave Roberts doesn’t think Shohei Ohtani heard fans in  Toronto taunting him  during Game 1 of the World Series on Friday night, and he doesn’t think the Japanese two-way sensation is bothered much by boos anyway. Upset that Ohtani spurned the Blue Jays to sign a $700 million contract with the Dodgers in December 2023, fans in Toronto chanted “We don’t need you!” when he came to the plate in the ninth inning with his team trailing by seven runs. Fans also booed Ohtani during pregame introductions. Ohtani appeared to smile at those jeers, but Roberts doesn’t think he caught the late barbs. Ohtani was booed and met with the same chant — but not from the entire crowd — leading off Game 2, when he flied out to left field. He was 1 for 4 in  Saturday’s 5-1 victory  that evened the Series. “I don’t think he understood the chants,” Roberts said before Game 2. “As far as being booed, I think that he understands why he was booed. I don’t think he minds it. I don’t think it necessarily fuels his fire. I’ve used this word with Shohei a lot: he’s just a really good compartmentalizer, so I don’t think it really affects him, and he’s just there to just do his job.” 



